text: hi everyone breathe in a deep Tano here
the internet's busiest music nerd and
it's time for a review of this new Trico
record fudeki this is the seventh
full-length LP from Kyoto rock outfit
Trico who have been dropping quite
frequently lately so much so that I
almost missed this new album here that
they put out just before the holidays
and given the title as well as the front
cover here I think it's pretty safe to
assume that this album is in one form or
another a sister album to their previous
full-length LP Jodeci which was a
refreshingly varied album for the band a
very colorful and mathy blend of
Japanese pop and rock with maybe some
jazz nuances tossed in here and there
from time to time and it sounds like on
this new on fudeki that the band's sense
of adventure is yet to be stifled
because you hear it all over the album's
Bold highlights it comes up in the
cheeky and playful fun guitars on a Choi
the speedily sung verses on this track
Coast into one of the smoothest and most
harmonious courses on the entire LP the
song gets even cuter and more explosive
as it progresses with these huge hits of
gang vocals and really crisp drums
there's also Joe Don kente with its
sweet and sticky vocal Melodies on the
verses delivered over these groovy drums
and shimmering beds of guitar that come
across kind of mysterious and strange
like the theme to a spy movie love the
intensity the song picks up on the back
end too as it becomes one of the most
riotest dance cuts on the lp then
there's end roll which I think has the
best vocal performance on the entire
record there's so many Nimble and
angular vocal Melodies on this track
some octave jumps too the band is really
firing on all cylinders with this track
but not losing their pop appeal in the
process and speaking of losing pop
appeal the band gets kind of Raw on the
track Android with a super
claustrophobic mix a lot of distortion
and some really overblown drums I have
been critical of some of the band's
tracks in the past sounding like
something along these lines but in this
instance it sounds very much intentional
that everything is so saturated is so
distorted and it does give them a little
bit of an edge this time around and kind
of a noise Rock appeal now Beyond this I
wouldn't say there are a lot of Duds on
the record but there are tracks that I
was kind of wanting more from the
transition into the chorus of UL is a
little uneventful in my opinion the
track ends so abruptly too the only
thing about it that really stands out is
that the drumming on it is absolutely
insane really the most relentless on the
entire record there's crumb which is a
slow burning ballad and I think there
are some admirable elements to this
track at its core the tune isn't too bad
the vocals do get more passionate as it
moves along but for the most part the
washed out guitar layers the
half-hearted performance overall just
kind of leaves uh the track feeling kind
of drab the more spacious mix and
impassioned singing on kujira is really
what makes that one the superior ballad
on the album even with some of the
guitar embellishments on this cut
sounding like some very limp post Rock
guitar twinkles my biggest issue with
the album Beyond here is that it doesn't
really stick the landing and I'm not
sure the band knows how to tie this
thing up there's aquarium which I think
is one of the most righteous songs on
the entire LP but it kind of sticks out
like a sore thumb because the sound and
performance on this track is a little
messy it's raw in the way that you might
expect from like a live recording or a
bootleg or something like that the mix
and instrumentation just comes across a
little flat much flatter than many of
the other more dolled up cuts on the
record then there's the title track
which is a kind of weak attempt in my
opinion at some 90s post grunge
Crossover with the way the riffs and
drums are vibing on this one though I
think trico's interpretation of this
sound is kind of awkward not nearly as
raw or wild or as hard hitting as you
would want something in this genre to be
and I think that is spelled out pretty
clearly in their attempt to come through
with like this kind of chaotic Nirvana
style endless nameless esque you know
finale here and it just doesn't really
come together all that well and it just
doesn't read as truly out of control or
chaotic then next there's a remix of the
title track from the last album uh kind
of finalizing things and I just don't
really see what's so transformative
about this remix outside of uh you know
some vocal bits being switched around
and it's much synthier I guess it's not
awful but I just failed to see what it
brings to this project and I would much
rather prefer to hear the original I
mean I think this record overall is a
pretty decent effort from Trico it's got
some great Tunes variety some good
production on most of the tracks They
continue to be one of the more standout
Japanese bands and math rock bands out
there today but I think this album Still
features some glaringly dull and
underwhelming moments that could have
been either left on The Cutting room
floor or improved in some form or
fashion I'm feeling a light 7 on this
